		<title>The Dying Earth Genre as Horror of the Irrational</title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational"/>
		<published>2013-01-27T13:16:39+00:00</published>
		<updated>2013-01-27T13:16:39+00:00</updated>
		<id>https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational</id>
		<author>
			<name>Michael Caton</name>
			<email>coady.k@protonmail.com</email>
		</author>
		<summary type="html">&lt;h3 class=&quot;story-teaser&quot;&gt;By Michael Caton&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;story-intro&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;story-thumb&quot; src=&quot;https://nightland.website/images/thumbs/coady-dying-earth-horror-irrational-thumb.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;beaten brass rings and a wrought iron spike spiralling down into the center of an orange vortex.&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;story-teaser&quot;&gt;The horror these authors convey at the extinction of reason is at the core of dying Earth prose, more important I think than the used-up Earth or the cooling Sun, and it's this that strikes a chord of unease in many readers, children of the Enlightenment as we are.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;feed-readmore&quot;&gt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational&quot;&gt;Read More ...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
		<content type="html">&lt;h3 class=&quot;story-teaser&quot;&gt;By Michael Caton&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;story-intro&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;story-thumb&quot; src=&quot;https://nightland.website/images/thumbs/coady-dying-earth-horror-irrational-thumb.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;beaten brass rings and a wrought iron spike spiralling down into the center of an orange vortex.&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;story-teaser&quot;&gt;The horror these authors convey at the extinction of reason is at the core of dying Earth prose, more important I think than the used-up Earth or the cooling Sun, and it's this that strikes a chord of unease in many readers, children of the Enlightenment as we are.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
